Key Terms

  • Groundwater is water stored in the open spaces (pores and fractures) within rocks and unconsolidated sediments below Earthâs surface.

  • Near-surface materials are under lower pressure, allowing for more open space to store water.

  • As a result, most groundwater accessed by individuals is within the first 100 metres.

  • Deeper groundwater is used by some municipal, agricultural, and industrial users but is often of lower quality and more costly to extract.

  • Aquifer: A layer of rock or sediment that stores and transmits groundwater.

  • Porosity: The percentage of open space in a rock or sediment that can store water.

  • Permeability: A measure of how easily water can flow through a material.

  • Water Table: The top of the saturated zone where all pore spaces are filled with water.

  • Recharge: The process of water entering and refilling an aquifer (e.g., from rain).

  • Discharge: Groundwater leaving an aquifer, naturally (e.g., springs) or by pumping.

  • Capillary Action: Water movement through narrow spaces due to adhesion and cohesion.

  • Fossil Water: Ancient groundwater that has been trapped in an aquifer for thousands to millions of years.

Porosity and Permeability

Source: https://deq.louisiana.gov

Porosity

  • Porosity is the percentage of total volume in a rock or sediment that consists of open (void) spaces.
  • Primary Porosity: Original spaces between grains (common in sediments and sedimentary rocks).
  • Secondary Porosity: Developed after rock formation (e.g., fractures, vesicles, solution cavities).

Permeability

  • Permeability is a measure of how easily water can flow through a rock or sediment.
  • It depends on the size, shape, and connectivity of the pores.
  • Hydraulic Conductivity (K) is used to quantify permeability (in metres/second).

Differences Between Porosity and Permeability

Feature Porosity Permeability
Definition Amount of void space in a material Ability of fluid to flow through the material
Influencing factors Grain size, sorting, cementation Pore size, connectivity, tortuosity, pore shape
High Example Silt and clay (porosity up to 70%) Gravel, sand, fractured rocks
Low Example Crystalline or compacted rocks Clay, unfractured igneous/metamorphic rocks

Note: A material like clay may have high porosity but low permeability due to small pore size and water binding to grain surfaces.

Importance in Groundwater Storage and Movement

  • Porosity controls how much water a rock or sediment can store.
  • Permeability controls how easily water can move through it.
  • Aquifers: Require high porosity and high permeability for effective water extraction.
  • Aquitards: May store water but restrict its movement due to low permeability.
  • Water moves from recharge to discharge zones, depending on hydraulic gradient and permeability.

Groundwater Formations

  • Aquifers
  • Aquitards
  • Aquicludes
  • Aquifuges

Aquifer

Source: https://theconstructor.org

An aquifer is a saturated geological formation that stores and yields groundwater in usable quantities. Aquifers are highly permeable, allowing water to move easily through them.

Types of Aquifers

  • Unconfined Aquifer:
    • Has a free water surface (water table).
    • Open to direct recharge from rainfall or surface infiltration.
    • Also called water table aquifer or phreatic aquifer.
  • Confined Aquifer:
    • Sandwiched between two impermeable layers (like clay or rock).
    • Water is under pressure and may rise in a well above the top of the aquifer (artesian conditions).
    • Recharge occurs where the aquifer is exposed at the surface.

Examples: Sand, gravel, sandstone, fractured limestone, fractured volcanic rocks

Aquitard

  • An aquitard is a saturated but partially permeable formation. It permits slow water movement but does not yield water efficiently like an aquifer.
  • It can allow slow seepage of water into underlying aquifers.
  • Typically composed of mixtures like sandy clay.

Aquiclude

  • An aquiclude is a geological formation that can store water but is impermeable to flow.
  • High porosity but very low or no permeability.
  • It contains water but does not allow it to pass through.
  • Example: Clay

Aquifuge

  • An aquifuge is a completely impermeable and non-porous geological unit.
  • Cannot store or transmit water.
  • Acts as a barrier to groundwater flow.
  • Example: Compact granite or dense crystalline rock

Groundwater Formations Summary

Formation Water Storage Permeability Water Yield Example
Aquifer High High (permeable) High Sand, gravel
Aquitard Moderate Low (partly permeable) Low (slow seepage) Sandy clay
Aquiclude High Very low None Clay
Aquifuge None None None Compact granite
  • Understanding these formations helps hydrogeologists make decisions about:
    • Well locations
    • Sustainable water use
    • Groundwater contamination risks
    • Aquifer recharge zones

Groundwater Flow

Groundwater does not flow like rivers underground â it moves slowly through pore spaces and fractures in soil and rock. Its movement is influenced by gravity and pressure differences, and it is governed by physical laws such as Darcyâs Law.

The Water Table and Hydraulic Gradient

Water Table

  • The water table is the top of the saturated zone in an unconfined aquifer.
  • It separates the unsaturated zone (air + water in pores) from the saturated zone (pores fully filled with water).
  • The water table rises and falls with changes in recharge (rainfall) and usage (pumping).

Hydraulic Gradient

  • The hydraulic gradient (i) is the slope of the water table or potentiometric surface.
    • A potentiometric surface is the imaginary plane where a given reservoir of fluid will âequalize out toâ if allowed to flow. A potentiometric surface is based on hydraulic principles. For example, two connected storage tanks with one full and one empty will gradually fill/drain to the same level (Wikiowdia).
  • It drives groundwater flow from high energy (high elevation or pressure) to low energy zones.

\[ i = \frac{{h_1 - h_2}}{{d}} \]

Where:
- \(h_1, h_2\): hydraulic head at two points
- \(d\): distance between the points

Darcyâs Law and Groundwater Velocity

In 1856, Henri Darcy described groundwater flow mathematically:

Darcyâs Law

\[ Q = K \cdot A \cdot i \]

Where:
- \(Q\): volumetric flow rate (mÂ³/s)
- \(K\): hydraulic conductivity (m/s)
- \(A\): cross-sectional area (mÂ²)
- \(i\): hydraulic gradient (unitless)

Darcy Flux and Velocity

  • Darcy Flux (q): flow per unit area: \[ q = K \cdot i \]
  • Actual groundwater velocity (v): \[ v = \frac{q}{n} \] Where \(n\) is porosity (as a decimal)

Groundwater velocity is usually very slow â often a few cm/day or less.

Recharge and Discharge Areas

  • Recharge Area: Region where water enters the groundwater system (e.g., rainfall infiltration).
  • Discharge Area: Where groundwater flows out (e.g., springs, wetlands, streams).
  • Water flows from recharge to discharge areas, following the hydraulic gradient.

Groundwater Flow Paths and Equipotential Lines

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Groundwater does not flow in straight lines.
  • It follows curved paths from high-pressure (high head) to low-pressure zones.
  • Flow is perpendicular to equipotential lines (lines of equal pressure).
  • Near discharge zones, groundwater can flow upward.

Key Concept:
- Groundwater flow resembles water flowing down a hill â it takes twisting paths through pores and fractures.
- No-flow boundaries occur where pressure gradients are zero â water doesnât move across these.

Karst Systems and Groundwater in Caves

  • Karst systems are formed in soluble rocks (e.g., limestone), creating:
    • Underground caves, tunnels, and sinkholes via dissolution.

Two Zones in Karst:

  • Above the water table:
    • Caves are air-filled.
    • Water moves quickly along cave floors under gravity.
  • Below the water table:
    • Caves are water-filled.
    • Water behaves like normal groundwater, following Darcyâs Law.
  • Karst aquifers often allow rapid and unpredictable groundwater movement â very different from typical porous media.

Groundwater Extraction and Monitoring

  • To use groundwater as a water resource, we must extract it through wells. This process involves careful planning, drilling, and monitoring to ensure sustainable use and avoid problems like over-pumping or water table decline.

Well Drilling, Construction, and Pumping

  • A well is a vertical shaft drilled into the ground to access groundwater in an aquifer.
  • Shallow wells may be hand-dug or drilled; deep wells require mechanical rigs.
  • Wells must reach below the water table to access water reliably.
  • A well casing (usually steel or plastic) is installed to support the well walls and prevent collapse.
  • A well screen is fitted at the bottom to allow water in but keep sediment out.
  • Water is lifted using submersible pumps or air-lift systems.
  • Well depth and construction depend on aquifer type and water demand.

Cones of Depression and Over-Pumping

Three wells in an unconfined aquifer. Well A is not being pumped. Well B is being pumped at a slow rate and well C, which has a larger cone of depression, is being pumped at a faster rate. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • When a well is pumped, it draws water from the surrounding aquifer.
  • This causes the water table (or potentiometric surface) to dip toward the well, forming a cone of depression.

Impacts of Over-Pumping:

  • Drying nearby wells (if cones of depression overlap).
  • Land subsidence (especially in clay-rich areas).
  • Reduction of baseflow to streams and ecosystems.
  • Saltwater intrusion in coastal areas.

Observation Wells and Groundwater Monitoring

  • Observation wells are non-pumping wells installed to monitor:
    • Water table levels
    • Aquifer pressure
    • Water quality
  • Many observation wells are equipped with automated sensors for real-time data.
  • Governments and agencies use these wells to detect trends and overuse.

Example:

  • British Columbia has 145+ active observation wells.
  • Data is available publicly to track seasonal and long-term changes.

Seasonal and Long-Term Changes in Groundwater Levels

Seasonal Changes:

  • Water levels drop during dry seasons (e.g., summer).
  • Water levels rise during wet seasons (e.g., winter), as recharge increases.

Long-Term Trends:

  • May show:
    • Decline due to over-pumping or drought.
    • Stability in balanced systems.
    • Recovery after conservation efforts.
  • Observation wells help distinguish natural variation from human impacts.

Summary (Groundwater Extraction and Monitoring)

Topic Key Points
Well Construction Requires casing, screen, and proper depth for reliability
Pumping Effects Causes cone of depression, may dry nearby wells
Over-Pumping Risks Can lead to land subsidence, stream drying, saltwater intrusion
Observation Wells Monitor water levels and quality without extracting water

Groundwater Contamination: Sources and Impacts

Although groundwater is often considered a clean and protected water source, it is vulnerable to contamination from both natural and human-made sources. Contamination can make water unsafe for drinking, irrigation, and ecosystems, and it is difficult and costly to clean once it occurs.

Natural Contamination

Some groundwater becomes contaminated naturally due to interaction with rocks and minerals in the aquifer.

Common Natural Contaminants:

  • Fluorine:
    • Found in rocks like volcanic ash or clays.
    • In high concentrations, causes fluorosis (dental and skeletal).
    • Example: Nanaimo Group aquifers (B.C.) with high-pH water mobilizing fluorine.
  • Arsenic:
    • Occurs in sediments under anoxic conditions (low oxygen).
    • Found in Bangladesh delta aquifers; linked to serious health problems (cancer, organ damage).
    • Solubility increases in reducing environments.

Anthropogenic (Human-Made) Contamination

Human activities at the surface (or underground) are a major source of groundwater pollution. Some sources release pollutants slowly over time, while others are caused by accidental spills or leaks.

A. Agriculture

  • Use of fertilizers and manure adds nitrates to the soil.

  • Excess nitrates can leach into shallow aquifers, especially in sandy soils.

  • Nitrate-contaminated groundwater poses health risks (e.g., âblue baby syndromeâ in infants).

  • Example: Abbotsford-Sumas aquifer (B.C.)ânitrate levels exceeded safe drinking limits due to poultry farming and berry crops.

B. Landfills and Leachate

  • Old dumpsites lacked protective liners; rainwater infiltrated and formed leachate.
  • Leachate contains chemicals, metals, and organics that may reach the aquifer.
  • Modern landfills use:
    • Plastic or clay liners
    • Leachate collection systems
    • Monitoring wells

C. Industrial Pollution

  • Factories and smelters may release toxic substances (e.g., lead, zinc, solvents).
  • Pollutants can leach into soil and groundwater.
  • Example: Trail, B.C.âlead and zinc smelter contaminated soils and groundwater.

D. Mines and Acid Rock Drainage (ARD)

  • Exposure of sulfide-rich rocks (e.g., pyrite) to air and water leads to formation of acidic water.
  • ARD increases metal solubility, polluting streams and groundwater.
  • Example: Mt. Washington Mine (Vancouver Island) â ARD with toxic copper runoff.

E. Leaking Underground Storage Tanks (USTs)

  • Gas stations and industrial sites use buried tanks for fuel.
  • Over time, tanks corrode and leak, contaminating groundwater with:
    • Petroleum hydrocarbons
    • Volatile organic compounds (VOCs)
  • Leaked fuel may:
    • Float on water table
    • Dissolve and spread
    • Vaporize and migrate toward surface

F. Septic Systems

  • Common in rural areas without sewage networks.
  • If not maintained properly, they can:
    • Leak untreated sewage into the soil
    • Contaminate shallow groundwater with bacteria, nitrates, and chemicals

Causes of Septic Failure:

  • Overflow from lack of pumping
  • Cracked or old tanks
  • Poor soil drainage or high water tables

Notes

  • Prevention is better than cleanup â most contaminated groundwater is extremely difficult to restore.
  • Solutions include:
    • Better land-use planning
    • Monitoring networks
    • Engineering controls (liners, caps, well design)
    • Groundwater modeling and risk mapping

Groundwater Protection and Remediation

Groundwater is a critical natural resource that is difficult to clean once contaminated. Protecting groundwater from pollution and applying effective remediation strategies are key parts of environmental and water resource management.

Preventing Groundwater Contamination

A. Physical Barriers

1. Caps and Covers

  • Used to prevent rainwater infiltration that could carry pollutants into the subsurface.
  • Common in:
    • Landfills
    • Mine tailings
    • Contaminated industrial sites

2. Liners

  • Impermeable barriers (plastic or engineered clay) placed beneath landfills or tailings ponds.
  • Prevent contaminated water (leachate) from seeping downward into aquifers.

Caps = Stop water from entering.
Liners = Stop water from escaping downward.

B. Land Use and Zoning Controls

  • Restricting hazardous activities above vulnerable aquifers
  • Requiring buffer zones around wells and recharge areas

Groundwater Remediation Strategies

Once contamination has occurred, remediation is often necessary. These techniques aim to stop further spread and to clean up existing pollution.

A. Pump-and-Treat

  • Contaminated groundwater is pumped to the surface, treated, and discharged or reinjected.
  • Common for:
    • Petroleum hydrocarbons
    • Metals
    • Industrial solvents

B. Containment

  • Involves hydraulic control using wells or physical barriers.
  • Goal: prevent plume from migrating toward sensitive areas (e.g., streams, drinking wells).

C. Manipulating Groundwater Flow

  • Strategic pumping from nearby wells can redirect flow away from vulnerable targets.
  • Injection wells can also be used to create a hydraulic barrier.

These methods are expensive and slow â prevention is always preferred.

Monitoring and Groundwater Legislation

A. Monitoring Wells

  • Non-pumping wells that measure:
    • Water table elevation
    • Water chemistry
    • Contaminant concentrations
  • Equipped with sensors or sampled manually.
  • Allow for:
    • Tracking contamination plumes
    • Assessing seasonal and long-term trends
    • Supporting management decisions ## B. Water Sustainability Act â British Columbia
  • Came into effect in 2016.
  • Key Features:
    • Licensing required for groundwater extraction (first time in B.C.)
    • Protects environmental flow needs â ensuring water for ecosystems (e.g., salmon habitat).
    • Supports long-term groundwater management using observation wells and aquifer mapping.

Other provinces and countries have similar legislation aimed at sustainable use and protection of groundwater.

Final Thought

Groundwater is invisible but essential â it supports drinking water, farming, and ecosystems. Protecting it requires planning, policy, and technology, and understanding hydrogeological principles is the first step.
